aa(lp280
VAnd one last powerful attribute
p281
aVthat comedy has as communication
p282
aVis that it's inherently viral.
p283
aVPeople can't wait
p284
aVto pass along that new great joke.
p285
aVAnd this isn't some new phenomenon of our wired world.
p286
aVComedy has been crossing country
p287
aVwith remarkable speed
p288
aVway before the Internet, social media,
p289
aVeven cable TV.
p290
aVBack in 1980
p291
aVwhen comedian Richard Pryor accidentally set himself on fire
p292
aVduring a freebasing accident,
p293
aVI was in Los Angeles the day after it happened
p294
aVand then I was in Washington D.C. two days after that.
p295
aVAnd I heard the exact same punchline on both coasts \u2014
p296
aVsomething about the Ignited Negro College Fund.
p297
aVClearly, it didn't come out of a Tonight Show monologue.
p298
aVAnd my guess here \u2014 and I have no research on this \u2014
p299
aVis that if you really were to look back at it and if you could research it,
p300
aVyou'd find out that comedy
p301
aVis the second oldest viral profession.
p302
aVFirst there were drums
p303
aVand then knock-knock jokes.
p304
aa(lp305
V(Laughter)
p306
aa(lp307
VBut it's when you put all of these elements together \u2014
p308
aVwhen you get the viral appeal of a great joke
p309
aVwith a powerful punchline
p310
aVthat's crafted from honesty and integrity,
p311
aVit can have a real world impact
p312
aVat changing a conversation.
